    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pitot tube, a little contraption that looks like a tiny, pointed nosecone, but don't let its unassuming appearance fool you. It's like a little spy, sneaking into the air and gathering vital information about the speed of your Cessna 172. When the air rushes into the pitot tube, it creates a pressure difference between the inside and outside, which is then converted into an airspeed reading. It's like a tiny, invisible hand, feeling the wind's speed and whispering it back to you.\n\nNow, if that pitot tube gets blocked up, it's like a sneaky goblin has thrown a wrench into the works. The air can't rush in, the pressure difference can't form, and suddenly, your airspeed reading is as reliable as a two-legged goblin trying to ride a dragon. It's a big deal because without accurate airspeed, you can't trust your instruments, and that's like flying blind in a world full of goblin traps and hidden pitfalls. So, keep that pitot tube clear, or you'll be flying through goblin-infested skies with no idea how fast you're going.",
